<ArticleLayout
  title="Laundry Tub Storage: What to Check Before Buying Under-Sink Organisers"
  description="Before buying laundry tub storage or under-sink organisers, check pipe clearance, leaks, moisture, cabinet depth, bottle height, door access and cleaning-product safety."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    The space under a laundry tub can look like useful storage, but it is often more awkward
    than it first appears.
  </p>
  <p>
    Pipes, hoses, taps, floor wastes, dampness, cleaning products, detergent bottles,
    buckets, brushes and small bins can all compete for the same space. In some homes, the
    cabinet under the laundry tub is deep enough to hide clutter but not easy enough to use
    well.
  </p>
  <p>
    The best first move is to look inside the cabinet with the door fully open. Pipes, hoses,
    damp corners and awkward door openings matter more than the outside dimensions.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good laundry tub storage system should make regular items easier to reach while still
    leaving plumbing visible and accessible. It should not hide leaks, block pipes, trap
    moisture or create unsafe cleaning-product storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader laundry planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-storage-what-to-measure-and-check-before-you-buy/">
      Laundry Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the real under-tub problem</h2>
  <p>Work out what is making the space difficult to use before adding an organiser.</p>
  <p>The problem may be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>pipes taking up the middle of the cabinet</li>
    <li>hoses reducing usable depth</li>
    <li>tall bottles not fitting upright</li>
    <li>cleaning products pushed to the back</li>
    <li>leaks or dampness</li>
    <li>baskets that cannot be removed easily</li>
    <li>no clear place for cloths, gloves or brushes</li>
    <li>products stored where children or pets can reach them</li>
    <li>a cabinet door that does not open wide enough</li>
    <li>a small laundry with very little nearby storage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Different problems need different solutions.</p>
  <p>
    If the main issue is tall bottles, a low shelf may not help. If products are hard to
    reach at the back, a removable basket may be more useful. If there are signs of leaks,
    storage should wait until the issue is fixed.
  </p>
  <p>The first step is to inspect the space, not fill it.</p>

  <h2>Check for leaks and dampness first</h2>
  <p>Do not add under-tub storage until the space has been checked for moisture.</p>
  <p>Look for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>water stains</li>
    <li>swollen cabinet panels</li>
    <li>musty smells</li>
    <li>soft or damaged cabinet flooring</li>
    <li>rust marks</li>
    <li>damp cloths or packaging</li>
    <li>drips around pipes</li>
    <li>leaks around hoses</li>
    <li>residue under detergent or cleaning bottles</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If the space is damp or leaking, fix the issue before adding storage.</p>
  <p>
    An organiser can hide early warning signs and make water damage harder to notice. This is
    especially important in a laundry because the area may already deal with wet towels,
    cleaning products and moisture from washing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing paper, cardboard, timber items or moisture-sensitive products under the tub
    if the area is damp.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure around the pipes</h2>
  <p>Laundry tub cabinets are rarely simple rectangles.</p>
  <p>Pipes and hoses can interrupt the most useful part of the cupboard.</p>
  <p>For shelves or baskets, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>internal cabinet width</li>
    <li>internal cabinet depth</li>
    <li>internal cabinet height</li>
    <li>pipe position from the left side</li>
    <li>pipe position from the right side</li>
    <li>pipe distance from the back wall</li>
    <li>height of the lowest pipe</li>
    <li>space in front of the pipes</li>
    <li>space beside the pipes</li>
    <li>whether hoses need movement or clearance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Do not rely on the outside cabinet size.</p>
  <p>
    A shelf may fit the width of the cabinet but still clash with the pipes. A pull-out
    basket may fit the floor space but fail because the pipe blocks the path.
  </p>
  <p>
    Adjustable or split-level organisers can be more useful than fixed shelves in awkward
    under-tub spaces.
  </p>

  <h2>Check door and hinge clearance</h2>
  <p>The cabinet opening may be smaller than the space inside.</p>
  <p>For baskets, caddies or pull-out storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>door opening width</li>
    <li>hinge position</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet has a centre divider</li>
    <li>whether both doors need to open</li>
    <li>whether handles or frames reduce access</li>
    <li>whether baskets can be pulled out straight</li>
    <li>whether products need to be tilted to remove them</li>
  </ul>
  <p>A basket that fits inside the cabinet is not helpful if it cannot be removed easily.</p>
  <p>This is common in older laundries, small rentals and narrow laundry cupboards.</p>

  <h2>Measure bottle and product height</h2>
  <p>Laundry tub storage often needs to hold tall products.</p>
  <p>For an organiser, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>laundry detergent bottles</li>
    <li>fabric softener if used</li>
    <li>stain removers</li>
    <li>spray bottles</li>
    <li>floor cleaners</li>
    <li>refill bottles</li>
    <li>buckets</li>
    <li>gloves</li>
    <li>brushes</li>
    <li>cleaning caddies</li>
    <li>small bins</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Products should usually stand upright.</p>
  <p>
    If bottles have to lie down to fit, they may leak or become harder to identify. A short
    organiser may also waste space if tall bottles need to sit beside it rather than inside
    it.
  </p>
  <p>
    For more cleaning-product planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/cleaning-product-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-cabinets-or-caddies/">
      Cleaning Product Storage: What to Check Before Buying Cabinets or Caddies</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide what belongs under the laundry tub</h2>
  <p>
    The under-tub area is usually best for items related to washing, cleaning and laundry
    maintenance.
  </p>
  <p>Common items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>laundry detergent</li>
    <li>stain remover</li>
    <li>cleaning sprays</li>
    <li>gloves</li>
    <li>cloths</li>
    <li>brushes</li>
    <li>bin liners</li>
    <li>spare sponges</li>
    <li>small buckets</li>
    <li>cleaning caddies</li>
    <li>pet cleaning supplies if used regularly</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>paper products</li>
    <li>electrical items</li>
    <li>food or pet food</li>
    <li>items damaged by moisture</li>
    <li>rarely used chemicals</li>
    <li>products children or pets can reach</li>
    <li>products that should be stored according to specific label directions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Do not treat the under-tub area as a general dumping zone.</p>
  <p>
    If the space stores too many unrelated items, it becomes harder to inspect, clean and
    use.
  </p>

  <h2>Match the organiser to the problem</h2>
  <p>Different under-tub organisers solve different problems.</p>

  <h3>Open baskets</h3>
  <p>Open baskets are simple and removable.</p>
  <p>They can help group detergent, sprays, cloths or gloves.</p>
  <p>
    Check whether bottles stand upright, whether the basket is easy to wipe clean, and
    whether it can be removed through the cabinet opening.
  </p>
  <p>Open baskets work best when the items need to be pulled out together.</p>

  <h3>Pull-out baskets</h3>
  <p>Pull-out baskets can help if items disappear at the back of a deep cabinet.</p>
  <p>
    Check whether the basket clears pipes, hinges, cabinet doors and any centre divider.
  </p>
  <p>
    In rentals, avoid pull-out systems that require permanent fixing unless approval is
    clear.
  </p>
  <p>A freestanding pull-out basket may be lower risk than one that needs screws.</p>

  <h3>Stackable shelves</h3>
  <p>Stackable shelves can add vertical storage if there is enough clear height.</p>
  <p>They may work beside the pipework or in one half of the cabinet.</p>
  <p>
    Check shelf height, pipe clearance and whether tall bottles can still stand upright.
  </p>
  <p>A shelf is not useful if it blocks access to products or makes leaks harder to spot.</p>

  <h3>Moisture-resistant trays</h3>
  <p>A tray can help contain small drips or residue from bottles.</p>
  <p>Check whether the tray is easy to remove and clean.</p>
  <p>A tray should not be used to ignore leaks. It is a practical cleaning aid, not a repair.</p>

  <h3>Cleaning caddies</h3>
  <p>A caddy may help if products move between the laundry, bathroom, kitchen or outdoor areas.</p>
  <p>
    Check handle comfort, bottle height, base stability and whether it becomes too heavy
    when full.
  </p>
  <p>A caddy should have a clear job. Otherwise, it may become another mixed container of forgotten products.</p>

  <h3>Small bins</h3>
  <p>Small bins may suit lint, packaging, used cloths or laundry waste.</p>
  <p>
    Check bin height, lid clearance and whether the bin can be removed without hitting pipes
    or doors.
  </p>
  <p>A bin that technically fits may still be annoying if it cannot be emptied easily.</p>

  <h2>Keep plumbing visible and accessible</h2>
  <p>Under-tub storage should not block access to pipes, hoses or fittings.</p>
  <p>Avoid packing the area so tightly that:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>leaks are hard to see</li>
    <li>pipes cannot be inspected</li>
    <li>hoses are bent or crowded</li>
    <li>products press against plumbing</li>
    <li>the cabinet is difficult to clean</li>
    <li>items fall behind the pipes</li>
    <li>maintenance access is blocked</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Leave enough clear space to see what is happening under the tub.</p>
  <p>
    If an organiser hides the entire cabinet floor or blocks the pipework, it may create more
    risk than convenience.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about children, pets and low storage</h2>
  <p>Under-tub storage is usually low and easy to reach.</p>
  <p>That matters if children or pets are in the home.</p>
  <p>Before storing cleaning products under the tub, consider:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the cabinet closes properly</li>
    <li>whether products are easy for children to reach</li>
    <li>whether pets can open or knock over items</li>
    <li>whether bottles can leak or tip</li>
    <li>whether products are stored according to their labels</li>
    <li>whether safer placement is needed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>A basket or shelf does not make cleaning products safe by itself.</p>
  <p>Follow product labels and choose storage that supports safer handling.</p>

  <h2>Consider renters and non-permanent options</h2>
  <p>Renters should be cautious with under-tub storage that requires permanent fixing.</p>
  <p>Renter-friendly options may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>removable baskets</li>
    <li>freestanding shelves</li>
    <li>loose trays</li>
    <li>portable caddies</li>
    <li>small bins</li>
    <li>non-permanent dividers</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Be careful with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>screw-fixed pull-out systems</li>
    <li>adhesive racks</li>
    <li>door-mounted organisers</li>
    <li>anything that marks cabinet doors or panels</li>
    <li>products that rely on one unusual cabinet shape</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you rent, choose storage that can be removed, cleaned and taken to another home.</p>
  <p>
    For small rental laundries, see:
    <a href="/guides/small-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-organisers/">
      Small Laundry Storage: What to Check Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid overfilling the cabinet</h2>
  <p>The space under the laundry tub should remain easy to inspect.</p>
  <p>Avoid filling it with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>too many cleaning products</li>
    <li>old detergent bottles</li>
    <li>duplicate sprays</li>
    <li>spare items with no clear use</li>
    <li>damp cloths</li>
    <li>loose packaging</li>
    <li>bulky buckets that block everything else</li>
    <li>items that belong in another room</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A crowded cabinet may look organised for a short time, but it often becomes harder to
    clean and maintain.
  </p>
  <p>In under-tub storage, less can be better.</p>

  <h2>Common laundry tub storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Laundry tub storage can go wrong when organisers are chosen before the space is checked.</p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying shelves before measuring pipe clearance</li>
    <li>ignoring signs of dampness or leaks</li>
    <li>choosing baskets that cannot be removed through the door opening</li>
    <li>storing bottles sideways because shelves are too short</li>
    <li>hiding leaks behind deep containers</li>
    <li>blocking access to pipes or hoses</li>
    <li>storing moisture-sensitive items under the tub</li>
    <li>putting cleaning products where children or pets can reach them</li>
    <li>using absorbent baskets for products that may leak</li>
    <li>overfilling the cabinet so it cannot be inspected</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The goal is not to use every centimetre. The goal is to make the space clearer, safer and
    easier to maintain.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy under-tub storage yet</h2>
  <p>You may not need a new organiser yet if the real issue is clutter or maintenance.</p>
  <p>First check whether the cabinet contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty detergent bottles</li>
    <li>old cleaning products</li>
    <li>duplicate sprays</li>
    <li>leaking bottles</li>
    <li>damp cloths</li>
    <li>products stored in the wrong room</li>
    <li>buckets or containers that block access</li>
    <li>items damaged by moisture</li>
    <li>signs of water damage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If removing these items clears the space, a new organiser may not be needed.</p>
  <p>If there is a leak, dampness or damage, deal with that before adding storage.</p>

  <h2>Simple laundry tub storage checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying laundry tub storage or under-sink organisers, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is the area dry and free from leaks?</li>
    <li>Have I measured around the pipes?</li>
    <li>Have I checked cabinet width, depth and height?</li>
    <li>Will bottles stand upright?</li>
    <li>Can baskets or trays be removed easily?</li>
    <li>Will the organiser block plumbing access?</li>
    <li>Is the material easy to clean?</li>
    <li>Can spills or leaks be seen quickly?</li>
    <li>Are cleaning products stored according to their labels?</li>
    <li>Is child or pet access a concern?</li>
    <li>Is it suitable for a rental if needed?</li>
    <li>Would removing clutter solve the issue first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Laundry tub storage works best when it is simple, removable and easy to inspect.</p>
  <p>
    Check the pipes, keep products upright, leave room for maintenance, and choose only the
    organisers that make the under-tub area clearer without hiding problems.
  </p>

